The error message "non-static method recupererParHebergement(int) cannot be referenced from a static context" indicates that you're trying to call a non-static method as if it were static. This is happening in your `calculateAverageRating` method where you're trying to call `AvisService.recupererParHebergement()`.

Here's how to fix it:

```java:src/main/java/controllers/ListesHebergController.java
// Calculate average rating
private float calculateAverageRating(int hebergementId) {
 try {
 // Change this line - use the instance, not the class
 List<AvisHebergement> avis = avisService.recupererParHebergement(hebergementId);

 if (avis.isEmpty()) {
 return 0.0f; // No reviews yet
 }

 float sum = 0;
 for (AvisHebergement a : avis) {
 sum += a.getReview();
 }

 return sum / avis.size();
 } catch (SQLException | UserNotFoundException e) {
 System.err.println("Error calculating average rating: " + e.getMessage());
 return 0.0f;
 }
}
```

Make sure you have the `avisService` instance defined as a field in your controller:

```java:src/main/java/controllers/ListesHebergController.java
// Near the top of your class, with other fields
private AvisService avisService = AvisService.getInstance();
```

If the `recupererParHebergement` method is specifically meant to be called statically, you need to update your AvisService class to make that method static:

```java:src/main/java/services/AvisService.java
public static List<AvisHebergement> recupererParHebergement(int idHeberg) throws SQLException, UserNotFoundException {
 // You would need to get a connection and service instances here
 Connection conn = MyConnection.getInstance().getConnection();
 UserService userService = UserService.getInstance();
 HebergementService hebService = HebergementService.getInstance();

 String sql = "SELECT * FROM avisHebergement WHERE idHeberg = ?";
 PreparedStatement st = conn.prepareStatement(sql);
 st.setInt(1, idHeberg);
 ResultSet rs = st.executeQuery();

 List<AvisHebergement> avisList = new ArrayList<>();
 while (rs.next()) {
 AvisHebergement avis = new AvisHebergement();
 avis.setIdAvis(rs.getInt("idAvis"));
 avis.setComment(rs.getString("comment"));
 avis.setReview(rs.getFloat("review"));
 avis.setUser(userService.getUserbyID(rs.getInt("idUser")));
 avis.setHebergements(hebService.recupererId(rs.getInt("idHeberg")));
 avisList.add(avis);
 }
 return avisList;
}
```

However, in most cases, it's better to use the instance method approach with the first solution I provided, as it's more consistent with your current architecture."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
