Then, update the `styleDialog` method in your `Helpers` class to apply the appropriate class based on the alert type:

```java:src/main/java/Util/Helpers.java
public static void styleDialog(Alert alert) {
 DialogPane dialogPane = alert.getDialogPane();

 // Add CSS stylesheet
 String css = Helpers.class.getResource("/styles/dialog-styles.css").toExternalForm();
 dialogPane.getStylesheets().add(css);
 dialogPane.getStyleClass().add("styled-dialog");

 // Add specific class based on alert type
 switch (alert.getAlertType()) {
 case ERROR:
 dialogPane.getStyleClass().add("error-dialog");
 break;
 case WARNING:
 dialogPane.getStyleClass().add("warning-dialog");
 break;
 case INFORMATION:
 dialogPane.getStyleClass().add("information-dialog");
 break;
 case CONFIRMATION:
 dialogPane.getStyleClass().add("confirmation-dialog");
 break;
 default:
 break;
 }

 // Style the buttons
 Button okButton = (Button) dialogPane.lookupButton(ButtonType.OK);
 Button cancelButton = (Button) dialogPane.lookupButton(ButtonType.CANCEL);
 Button yesButton = (Button) dialogPane.lookupButton(ButtonType.YES);
 Button noButton = (Button) dialogPane.lookupButton(ButtonType.NO);

 // Apply styling only to buttons that exist
 if (okButton != null) okButton.getStyleClass().add("dialog-button");
 if (cancelButton != null) cancelButton.getStyleClass().add("dialog-button");
 if (yesButton != null) yesButton.getStyleClass().add("dialog-button");
 if (noButton != null) noButton.getStyleClass().add("dialog-button");

 // Add icon
 try {
 Stage stage = (Stage) dialogPane.getScene().getWindow();
 stage.getIcons().add(new Image(Helpers.class.getResourceAsStream("/logo/Cartago_6.png")));
 } catch (Exception e) {
 System.err.println("Could not load icon: " + e.getMessage());
 }
}
```

This approach uses standard CSS classes instead of pseudo selectors. When styling dialogs, the system will add the appropriate class (like `error-dialog` or `confirmation-dialog`) based on the alert type, and your CSS will style them accordingly.

If you still encounter issues, here's an even simpler approach that should definitely work:

```java:src/main/java/Util/Helpers.java
public static void styleDialog(Alert alert) {
 DialogPane dialogPane = alert.getDialogPane();

 // Add CSS stylesheet
 String css = Helpers.class.getResource("/styles/dialog-styles.css").toExternalForm();
 dialogPane.getStylesheets().add(css);

 // Set header panel background color based on alert type
 String headerStyle = "";
 String headerTextColor = "white";

 switch (alert.getAlertType()) {
 case ERROR:
 headerStyle = "-fx-background-color: #d9534f;";
 break;
 case WARNING:
 headerStyle = "-fx-background-color: #f0ad4e;";
 break;
 case INFORMATION:
 headerStyle = "-fx-background-color: #5bc0de;";
 break;
 case CONFIRMATION:
 headerStyle = "-fx-background-color: #012e41;";
 break;
 default:
 headerStyle = "-fx-background-color: #012e41;";
 break;
 }

 // Apply inline styles directly to the header panel
 dialogPane.lookup(".header-panel").setStyle(headerStyle + 
 "-fx-background-radius: 15 15 0 0; -fx-padding: 15 15 15 15;");

 // Style buttons directly
 dialogPane.getButtonTypes().stream()
 .map(dialogPane::lookupButton)
 .forEach(button -> {
 button.setStyle("-fx-background-color: #FA7335; -fx-text-fill: white; " +
 "-fx-background-radius: 20; -fx-padding: 8 20 8 20;");

 // Add hover effect with event handlers
 button.setOnMouseEntered(e -> 
 button.setStyle("-fx-background-color: #ff8d59; -fx-text-fill: white; " +
 "-fx-background-radius: 20; -fx-padding: 8 20 8 20;"));

 button.setOnMouseExited(e -> 
 button.setStyle("-fx-background-color: #FA7335; -fx-text-fill: white; " +
 "-fx-background-radius: 20; -fx-padding: 8 20 8 20;"));
 });

 // Style the dialog background
 dialogPane.setStyle("-fx-background-color: #f8f9fa; -fx-padding: 20; -fx-background-radius: 15;");

 // Add icon
 try {
 Stage stage = (Stage) dialogPane.getScene().getWindow();
 stage.getIcons().add(new Image(Helpers.class.getResourceAsStream("/logo/Cartago_6.png")));
 } catch (Exception e) {
 System.err.println("Could not load icon: " + e.getMessage());
 }
}
```

This approach uses inline styles rather than CSS classes, which can be more reliable when dealing with JavaFX's styling limitations."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
