You can play music when your application starts by using JavaFX's built-in media classes. Here's how to add background music to your `testClient.java` file:

```java:src/main/java/test/testClient.java
package test;

import javafx.application.Application;
import javafx.fxml.FXMLLoader;
import javafx.scene.Scene;
import javafx.scene.layout.BorderPane;
import javafx.scene.media.Media;
import javafx.scene.media.MediaPlayer;
import javafx.stage.Screen;
import javafx.stage.Stage;
import javafx.util.Duration;

import java.io.File;
import java.net.URL;

public class testClient extends Application {

 private MediaPlayer mediaPlayer;

 public static void main(String[] args) {
 launch(args);
 }

 @Override
 public void start(Stage primaryStage) {
 try {
 // Start playing background music
 playBackgroundMusic();

 // Load the FXML file for the Home UI
 FXMLLoader loader = new FXMLLoader(getClass().getResource("/views/SignIn.fxml"));
 BorderPane root = loader.load();

 // Create the Scene from the FXML root layout
 Scene scene = new Scene(root);

 /* double screenWidth = Screen.getPrimary().getBounds().getWidth();
 double screenHeight = Screen.getPrimary().getBounds().getHeight();

 // Set stage size based on screen size
 primaryStage.setWidth(screenWidth * 0.8); // 80% of screen width
 primaryStage.setHeight(screenHeight * 0.8); // 80% of screen height*/

 // Set the title of the window
 primaryStage.setTitle("Home");

 // Set the Scene to the primaryStage
 primaryStage.setScene(scene);

 // Show the Stage (window)
 primaryStage.show();

 // Stop music when the application closes
 primaryStage.setOnCloseRequest(event -> {
 if (mediaPlayer != null) {
 mediaPlayer.stop();
 }
 });

 } catch (Exception e) {
 e.printStackTrace();
 }
 }

 /**
 * Plays background music for the application
 */
 private void playBackgroundMusic() {
 try {
 // Path to your music file (place it in the resources folder)
 // You can use either a file path or a resource URL

 // Option 1: Using resource URL (recommended)
 URL resourceUrl = getClass().getResource("/music/background_music.mp3");
 if (resourceUrl != null) {
 Media media = new Media(resourceUrl.toString());
 mediaPlayer = new MediaPlayer(media);

 // Set properties for the media player
 mediaPlayer.setCycleCount(MediaPlayer.INDEFINITE); // Loop indefinitely
 mediaPlayer.setVolume(0.3); // Set volume to 30%

 // Play the music
 mediaPlayer.play();

 // Optional: Fade in the music
 mediaPlayer.setVolume(0);
 mediaPlayer.setOnPlaying(() -> {
 javafx.animation.Timeline timeline = new javafx.animation.Timeline(
 new javafx.animation.KeyFrame(Duration.seconds(3),
 new javafx.animation.KeyValue(mediaPlayer.volumeProperty(), 0.3)));
 timeline.play();
 });
 } else {
 System.err.println("Could not find music file in resources");
 }

 /* Option 2: Using file path (alternative)
 String musicFile = "src/main/resources/music/background_music.mp3";
 File file = new File(musicFile);
 if (file.exists()) {
 Media media = new Media(file.toURI().toString());
 mediaPlayer = new MediaPlayer(media);
 mediaPlayer.setCycleCount(MediaPlayer.INDEFINITE);
 mediaPlayer.setVolume(0.3);
 mediaPlayer.play();
 } else {
 System.err.println("Music file not found: " + musicFile);
 }
 */

 } catch (Exception e) {
 System.err.println("Error playing background music: " + e.getMessage());
 e.printStackTrace();
 }
 }

 /**
 * Add these methods to control the music from other parts of your application
 */
 public void pauseMusic() {
 if (mediaPlayer != null) {
 mediaPlayer.pause();
 }
 }

 public void resumeMusic() {
 if (mediaPlayer != null) {
 mediaPlayer.play();
 }
 }

 public void setVolume(double volume) {
 if (mediaPlayer != null) {
 mediaPlayer.setVolume(volume);
 }
 }
}
```

## Setting Up Your Music Resources

1. Create a folder named `music` in your resources directory: `src/main/resources/music/`
2. Add your MP3 file to this folder, for example: `background_music.mp3`

## Dependencies

Make sure you have the JavaFX media module in your project dependencies:

### For Maven:
```xml
<dependency>
 <groupId>org.openjfx</groupId>
 <artifactId>javafx-media</artifactId>
 <version>17.0.2</version> <!-- Use your JavaFX version -->
</dependency>
```

### For Gradle:
```groovy
implementation 'org.openjfx:javafx-media:17.0.2' // Use your JavaFX version
```

## Key Features of This Implementation

1. **Background Music Playing**:
 - Starts playing automatically when the application launches
 - Loops continuously until the application is closed
 - Has a soft volume (30%) so it's not intrusive

2. **Resource Management**:
 - Loads music from resources folder (more reliable than file paths)
 - Provides fallback with file path option if needed
 - Proper error handling if music file isn't found

3. **Music Controls**:
 - Added methods for pausing, resuming, and adjusting volume
 - Can be called from other controllers if you expose these methods properly
 - Clean shutdown when the application closes

4. **Optional Effects**:
 - Volume fade-in for a smoother start
 - Can be easily modified to add fade-out or other effects

5. **Memory Management**:
 - Properly stops the MediaPlayer when the application closes to free resources

## Additional Considerations

If you want to give users control over the music, you can add buttons to your UI:

```java
// In your controller class:
@FXML
private void toggleMusic() {
 testClient app = (testClient) getApplication();
 if (musicPlaying) {
 app.pauseMusic();
 musicPlaying = false;
 } else {
 app.resumeMusic();
 musicPlaying = true;
 }
}

@FXML
private void adjustVolume(double value) {
 testClient app = (testClient) getApplication();
 app.setVolume(value);
}
```

Remember that some users might not want background music, so it's a good practice to provide a way to turn it off or adjust the volume."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
